      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Let's break down the calculation for the first two years of depreciation using the 200% declining balance method.\n\nIn the first year, the equipment's value decreases by 200% of its cost, which is:\n\n200% of $100,000 = 2 x $100,000 = $200,000\n\nSo, the equipment's value at the end of the first year is:\n\n$100,000 - $200,000 = -$100,000 (it's now depreciated by $100,000)\n\nHowever, since we can't have a negative value, we'll use the half-year convention. This means that we'll allocate the depreciation over two half-years. So, the first-year depreciation would be:\n\n$100,000 x 200% / 2 = $100,000 x 100% = $100,000\n\nThis means the equipment's value at the end of the first half-year is:\n\n$100,000 - $50,000 = $50,000\n\nIn the second year, the equipment's value decreases by 200% of its value at the end of the first half-year, which is:\n\n200% of $50,000 = 2 x $50,000 = $100",
